          "body": "Verse 13 is the theological center of Proverbs 28 and one of the most pastorally concentrated couplets in the entire book: 'He who conceals his transgressions will not prosper, but he who confesses and forsakes them will find compassion.' The Hebrew is surgical. *Kasah* (conceal) is the act of covering, managing, and suppressing awareness of one's own *pesah* — the same word for covenant rebellion that appears in verses 2 and 24. The one who conceals will not *tsalach* (prosper, succeed, advance). The negative is categorical, not probabilistic. Against it stands *yadah* (confess) paired with *azav* (forsake) — two verbs, not one. Confession without forsaking is incomplete; forsaking without honest naming is self-deception. Both together lead to *racham* — the tender, covenant-soaked compassion of a God who is characteristically merciful toward honest sinners. This verse is Proverbs' deepest convergence with the Psalmic theology of Psalm 32:3–5 and the New Covenant provision of 1 John 1:9."
