          "title": "Fear of the LORD as the alternative to hardness of heart",
          "body": "Verse 14 supplies the positive alternative to verse 13's concealer: *How blessed is the man who fears always.* The word *pachad* is sometimes translated reverence but carries the note of trembling, healthy dread — a sustained posture of moral alertness before the holiness of God. The 'always' (*tamid*, continually) is crucial: this is not the fear that activates at a crisis moment but the ongoing orientation of a life that has not lost its sense of who God is and what He requires. The contrast in v. 14b is devastating: *he who hardens his heart will fall into calamity* — *qashah lev*, the hardening of Pharaoh (Exodus 7–11), is the catastrophic alternative to perpetual reverence. The hardened heart is not merely indifferent; it is actively resisting the impressions of God's word and refusing to be moved by what should move it. Verse 14 is the interior of verse 13: the man who fears always is the man who does not conceal his transgressions, because the fear of God makes self-deception intolerable."
